SIMPLE: inveteracy
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Inveteracy
<hw>In*vet"er*a*cy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From
<er>Inveterate</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Firm establishment by long continuance; firmness or
deep-rooted obstinacy of any quality or state acquired by time; <as>as,
the <ex>inveteracy</ex> of custom, habit, or disease</as>; -- usually in
a bad sense; <as>as, the <ex>inveteracy</ex> of prejudice or of
error</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>An <qex>inveteracy</qex> of evil habits that will prompt him to
contract more.</q> <rj><qau>A. Tucker.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Malignity; spitefulness; virulency.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The rancor of pamphlets, the <qex>inveteracy</qex> of epigrams,
and the mortification of lampoons.</q> <rj><qau>Guardian.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Inveterate</ent>⟦br⟧
